EXAMPLE.SOLUTION:
When we add together two matrices we add together the elements term by term as shown here:
\begin{equation}
\left(
 \begin{matrix}
  a & b \\
  c & d
 \end{matrix}
\right) + 
\left(
 \begin{matrix}
  e & f \\
  g & h
 \end{matrix}
\right) = 
\left(
 \begin{matrix}
  a + e & b + f \\
  c + g & d + h
 \end{matrix}
\right)
\end{equation}

When a matrix is multiplied by a scalar the scalar multiplies each of the elements of the matrix in turn
as shown here:
\begin{equation}
\alpha \left(
 \begin{matrix}
  a & b \\
  c & d
 \end{matrix}
\right) = 
\left(
 \begin{matrix}
  \alpha a & \alpha b \\
  \alpha c & \alpha d
 \end{matrix}
\right)
\end{equation}
